Here is the compacted version of the argument, distilled to its core architectural mechanics and hard numbers for maximum impact:1. The Write-Path I/O BottleneckThe fundamental limit lies in how each database handles per-event I/O and storage mechanics.PostgreSQL (Random I/O & Thrashing): A single insert requires three writes: WAL, heap tuple, and B-tree index. Because sensor_ids arrive randomly, B-tree updates scatter across the index. At 40,000 events/sec, this overwhelms the shared buffer pool, causing cache thrashing. Index updates become expensive read-then-write operations, pushing write amplification to 3–5×. Furthermore, periodic checkpoints must flush gigabytes of dirty pages (e.g., 1.4 GB every 5 minutes) to disk, creating massive I/O spikes that compete with the insert stream.Cassandra (Sequential I/O): Writes are sequential and memory-first. An event hits the CommitLog (sequential append) and the MemTable (in RAM). No disk reads are required, and no B-trees are traversed. This keeps write amplification down to 1–1.5×.2. Throughput Ceilings vs. The GridSense GapApplying these first principles to GridSense’s requirements reveals a structural mismatch.SystemSustained Write Limit (Single Node)Architectural BottleneckGridSense Target40k sustained, 120k peakN/APostgreSQL20k – 30k inserts/secRandom B-tree maintenance with compound indexes.Cassandra100k – 200k inserts/secSequential limit; scales linearly by adding nodes without cross-node coordination.3. The TimescaleDB CaveatWhile the senior engineer is correct that TimescaleDB improves PostgreSQL's time-series performance, it does not solve the fundamental scaling limit.TimescaleDB converts inserts to append-only chunks, bypassing B-tree scatter and pushing single-node throughput to 80,000–100,000 inserts/sec. However, this still fails to meet GridSense's 120,000 peak load. Scaling PostgreSQL further horizontally requires extensions like Citus, which reintroduces distributed coordination overhead on cross-shard queries — hitting the exact relational scaling limit highlighted by Kleppmann.